Test Case ID,Title,Preconditions,Steps,Expected Result
LT‑NOM‑001,Baseline “Cold‑Start” Load Test (10 k nominations submitted sequentially),"• Test environment mirrors production (DB, API gateway, services).  • Nomination data generator ready with 10 k valid records.  • Monitoring tools (CPU, memory, DB latency, response‑time charts) are active.","1. Start monitoring. 2. Execute the data‑generator script to POST each nomination one after another (no think‑time). 3. After the last request, stop monitoring. 4. Export logs and response‑time metrics.","• All 10 k nominations are persisted without any 5xx or 4xx errors. • Average response time ≤ the threshold defined with product (e.g., ≤ 2 s). • No critical server‑side exceptions in logs. • Resource usage stays within safe limits (CPU < 80 %, RAM < 75 %)."
LT‑NOM‑002,Gradual Ramp‑Up Load Test (peak concurrency 200 users),"• Same environment as TC‑001. • Load‑testing tool (e.g., JMeter, Gatling) configured with a ramp‑up schedule. • Acceptance threshold for max response time defined (e.g., ≤ 3 s).","1. Start monitoring. 2. Begin ramp‑up: 0 → 200 virtual users over 5 min. 3. Each virtual user continuously submits nominations until a total of 10 k requests is reached. 4. Capture response times, error rates, and system metrics. 5. Stop the test and collect logs.",• System processes the full 10 k requests with error rate ≤ 1 %. • 95th‑percentile response time ≤ the defined threshold (≤ 3 s). • No database deadlocks or connection‑pool exhaustion. • CPU/Memory spikes are transient and return to baseline within 2 min after load ends.
LT‑NOM‑003,"Sustained Load Test (10 k nominations over 30 min, constant 150 concurrent users)","• Environment as above. • Acceptance criteria for sustained throughput (e.g., ≥ 333 req/min).","1. Start monitoring. 2. Launch 150 virtual users that each submit a nomination every 5 seconds (steady‑state). 3. Continue for 30 minutes (≈ 9 k requests) then add a final burst of 1 k requests to reach 10 k total. 4. Record throughput, latency, and any resource saturation.",• Throughput remains ≥ 333 requests/min throughout the 30‑min window. • No increase in error rate over time (steady ≤ 1 %). • System resources stay within defined limits; no memory leaks or GC pauses > 500 ms. • All 10 k nominations are stored correctly.
LT‑NOM‑004,Peak‑Concurrency Spike Test (10 k nominations with a sudden 1 000‑user burst),"• Same baseline environment. • Spike‑threshold for response time defined (e.g., ≤ 5 s for 99 % of requests).","1. Warm‑up the system with 200 users for 2 min. 2. Immediately inject a spike of 1 000 additional users (total 1 200 concurrent) for 30 seconds, each sending a nomination request. 3. After the spike, return to the warm‑up level for another 2 min. 4. Capture error rates, response‑time distribution, and server metrics.",• System absorbs the spike without critical failures (error rate ≤ 2 %). • 99 % of requests during the spike complete within ≤ 5 s. • No request queue overflow or timeout errors. • All 10 k nominations are eventually persisted (including those sent during the spike).
LT‑NOM‑005,Post‑Test Reporting & Validation,• All previous test runs completed and logs collected. • Access to stakeholder reporting template.,"1. Aggregate results from TC‑001‑004 (response‑time charts, error‑rate tables, resource‑utilization graphs). 2. Verify data integrity: query the database to confirm exactly 10 k new nomination records with correct status. 3. Populate the load‑test report (objective, methodology, findings, risks, recommendations). 4. Review the report with product/tech leads and obtain sign‑off.","• A comprehensive test report is produced, containing:  • Summary of each test case, metrics, and pass/fail status.  • Evidence that the system handled 10 k entries without critical failures.  • Response‑time figures all within agreed thresholds.  • Recommendations for any observed bottlenecks. • Stakeholders receive the report and formally acknowledge acceptance."